name: Miss Clark
title: Miss
notes: The timeline of Miss Clark's lending library membership is confusing. On June 2, 1925, she purchased a one month membership, which allowed her to borrow one volume at a time. On June 16, 1925, she paid to extend that membership to a full year. On September 22, 1925, she traded her one-year, one-volume-at-a-time membership for a two-month, two-volume-at-a-time membership! Her membership, thus, began on June 6, 1925 and ended on November 2, 1925.

notes: Max Allen Egloff was a journalist and civil servant, and was married the economist [Marjorie Ruth Clark](http://viaf.org/viaf/213374287). In a letter to his mother on May 26, 1923, he writes: "Really my pleasures and annoyances are now reduced to those incident to routine existence in Paris. Once in awhile comes an unusual pleasure such as meeting Hemingway, a young American writer of moderate distinction. I was introduced to him yesterday by Noyes who met him at the Shakespeare bookstore, a hangout for English and American writers. [...] The Shakespeare library which I mentioned is proving a great help, Slyia Beach [sic], the proprietress, maintains a large lending library containing most of the books in which I am particularly interested at this time."

name: Terence Philip
title: Mr.
addresses: Hôtel Foyot, 33 rue de Tournon, Paris;5 Portman Place, London
notes: Terence Philip was born in Moscow in 1891. (His father, Walter, was co-owner of the Moscow department store, Muir and Mirrlees.) During World War I, Terence was a prisoner of war in Ruhleben, a German internment camp. In 1920, he published a book of poems, [*Poems: Written at Rhuleben*](https://archive.org/details/poemswrittenatru00philiala/page/n5/mode/2up). After the war, he worked in the diplomatic services in Italy and eventually for the art dealer [Wildenstein & Company](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wildenstein_%26_Company). He is most often remembered, for his relationship with [Clementine Churchill](https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/first-lady-the-life-and-wars-of-clementine-churchill-by-sonia-purnell-70f0jxfhqgv).

name: Franz Thomassin
notes: From Claude Arnaud's *Jean Cocteau: A Life* (2003, 2016): "Franz, the strangest of the three, became the most devoted, and took took a room at the Hôtel de la Madeleine. Tall, thin, and muscular, with Slavic cheekbones and a piercing gaze that would inspire Matisse, this dilettante was overwhelmed with such paralyzing pride that his very nobility gave him complexes. 'The most Roussel-ian character since [Raymond] Roussel,' wrote Sachs in *Au temps du Boeuf sur le Toit,* 'but with tact and kindness, even an excess of kindness, like Proust, which hurt him: he had a beaten air, but a tender, proud, and congenial one.' Cocteau tried at first to 'read' this living mystery, who would spend his whole life not writing the books he had promised to write. By turns obsequious and exhibitionist, Franz Thomassin protected himself from others with virginal modesty or audacious timidity" (555).

name: Hélène Yelin

Yelin mentions that she posed for a [sculpture](https://collection.beta.fitz.ms/id/image/media-183282) by Jacob Epstein. [UK Art Detective](https://www.artuk.org/artdetective/discussions/discussions/is-the-sitter-the-bookbinder-helene-cox) discusses Yelin's biography.
